cards.description:
AMIE Locations - based on Farallon
Design summary

> Addresses
	Model Address as a semanitic node (E45 Address) 
	Locations (top node of bracnch) P87_is_identified_by Addresses


> Description
	Includes directions


> Property Ownership (Cadastral Reference)
	Modeled as E42 Identifier because parcel identifiers are meant to uniquely and permanently refere to a specifc area of land ownership


> Admin/Related Areas
	Modeled as E53 Place
	Locations (top node of branch) P121_overlaps_with Adminstrative/Related Areas

	Used to manage:
		Admin area
		Geopolitical areas
		Localities
		Other areas (such as zoning, special use, archaeological research areas)


> Map References
	Modeled as E44 Place_Appellation
	Locations (top node of branch) P1_is_identified_by Map References

	Used to manage 
		National Grid References
		Map sheets

graph.description:
This includes buildings (both ruined and in use), shipwrecks and aircraft crash sites, as well as field monuments such as barrows and field systems, wetlands, cropmarks, submerged landscapes, urban strata and find-spots typically associated with archaeology. The focus is on the ‘thing’ itself in this Information Group. Records of investigation of these features (e.g. archaeological excavations) are covered by Information Groups in the Activity theme.
The broad definition of monument extends to the recording of the former existence of buildings or archaeological remains now destroyed (e.g. by quarrying or urban development). The knowledge of these sites contributes to the overall understanding of the historic environment.
graph.name: MIDAS Heritage Asset - Monument (Only missing phasing and evidence)
